infrastructure up there, everything else will follow.&quot; <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with you...totally <br>
<br>
I don't particularly follow that every endeavor in space should follow one mantra that things in space should always be cheaper...frankly, I subscribe to, things that work in space the way they're designed to work...Does that mean it could be done cheaper? Yes, I would agree. But it shouldn't be the only rule in manufacture, novel space technology initial costs are always higher once the learning curve has been flattened. Most materials for reactors have to be made from scratch sometimes with plenty of existing data sets and sometimes materials are drawn from research. I doubt material is gathered by shopping at the local home depot store.<br>
<br>
The advantage to keeping cost down is that the DOE facilities<br>
to test designs have for the most part been paid for by the U.S. tax payer last century. Teams that design and build nuclear space systems don't like re-inventing the wheel they use data from previous research whenever they can.<br>
<br>
As far as nuke vs. chemical in space, nuke has Isp efficiency over chemical, nuke can be shut down and fired back up countless times without a misfire. So long as reactor core manufacture is sound and rocket engine components sound there should be average to minimal maintenance in space.<br>
<br>
And like with any heat source in space it must be cared for meaning heat/cooling management for strict operational and safety guideline have to be followed.<br>
<br>
Chemical propulsion will rule from sea level to LEO and at LEO and to and from planet/moon to low planet/moon orbit and for short distance shuttles but serious solar system thrust to weight travel hauls will require nukes: fission,fusion,antimatter-no question about that . <br>
