<br>
To most people, space exploration is dull and dead.<br>
<br>
Polls consistently show that people don't want to spend money and resources on a Mars trip.<br>
<br>
I have a speculation about what ~some~, not all,  of the problem is.<br>
<br>
I grew up during the race into space. I was 5 when the first satellite went into orbit, and 17 when Apollo 11 landed on the Moon, and the Adventure of Space ended.<br>
<br>
With minor exceptions, the real space program was ahead of ordinary peoples perceptions. It was a fascinating and exciting new world. By the 70's and 80's, science fiction films and TV became quite common, and showed  unlimited and instant travel thruout the galaxy. The mundane amd slow pace of the real space program became incredibly limited, and dull and boring compared to hyperspace travel in galactic empires.<br>
<br>
The real space program (except to science geeks like ourselves) was as exciting as watching a railroad  switch yard as compared to the NASCAR race of Star Wars.<br>
<br>
I don't have any real answers.<br>
<br>
What do you think it will take?<br>
